<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>Infinitive is a non-finite verb form. It is not declined for person
or number but is found in all voices and in present, aorist, future and
perfect tenses.</p>
<p>Infinitive is an obligatory constituent to verbs denoting desire or
will – the so-called dynamic infinitive verbs of saying and thinking –
the so-called declarative infinitive (Rijksbaron 2006, 96-7)</p>
<p>ACI: Articular infinitive Articular infinitive is governed by the
neuter singular article which is declined normally.</p>
<h2 id="examples-of-infitive-mood-from-papygreek-corpus">Examples of
infitive mood from PapyGreek corpus</h2>
<ol type="1">
<li>οὐκ ἔφη οὖν <strong>δύνασθαι</strong> οὐκέτι
<strong>παραπλ[εῖν]</strong><br>
(ouk éphē oûn <strong>dúnasthai</strong> oukéti
<strong>parapleîn</strong>)<br>
<em>So he said that he was not able to sail by at the moment</em>.<br>
<a href="https://papygreek.com/text/24027">p.cair.zen.1.59093.</a>, 8
(sent. 7), transl. Sari Kock.</li>
</ol>
